Introduction¶

  • The aim of this analysis is to cluster commercial electricity users based on consumption profiles using feature extraction (PCA) and machine learning clustering algorithms (K-Means and DBSCAN).
  • The growth of intermittent electricity generation sources, such as wind, solar etc., on electricity grids has increased the challenge of balancing supply and demand. Instead of increasing supply to meet demand, shifting or curtailing demand using time-of-use tariffs and demand-side response has become increasingly important.
  • In order to offer the appropriate time-of-use tariff and DSR products and incentives to users, it is useful for electricity suppliers and operators to have a clear understanding of user profiles. Fairly simple user categorisation based on industry or business type (e.g. office, grocer, school etc.) are insufficent as there can be significant variation in consumption profiles within these categories.
  • The hypothesis of this study is that a machine learning clustering approach can provide more suitable and insightful user categorisation.
  • This study uses anonymized 5-minute energy usage data for 100 commercial/ industrial sites for 2012 (Available at:https://open-enernoc-data.s3.amazonaws.com/anon/index.html). Commercial users in the dataset are currently categorised according to industry and sub-industry.

3. Modelling¶

This section will follow these steps:

  1. Conduct PCA on 5-minute yearly readings
    • The dataset has high-dimensionality (100 x 105407). K-Means uses the distance between points to create clusters. The high-dimesionality can cause issues such as the 'curse of dimensionality', whereby the sparsity of data points reduces the ability of the algorithm to identify meaningful clusters, and increased computational requirements.
    • Therefore, a principal component analysis (PCA) was conducted to reduce the dimensionality of the dataset before clustering.
  2. K-Means
    • Perform K-Means clustering.
  3. DBSCAN
    • Perform DBSCAN clustering.

3.2 K-Means¶

  • For K-Means the number of clusters must be specified as a parameter. An elbow plot is often used to find the optimum number of clusters. The elbow plot is designed to show the point at which increasing the number of clusters does not result in increasing inertia (Inertia = within-cluster sum-of-squares. A low value is better because it indicates more compact clustering).
  • Increased numbers of clusters is often assiciated with a decrease in interpretability.
  • The silhoutte score can also be used as a clustering metric (silhouette score = a measurement of average distances between within- and outside- cluster points with values between 1 and -1. A high value is an indicator of well separated clusters.)
  • This analysis will use inertia and silhouette plots to evaluate the optimum number of clusters.
In [17]:
import warnings
warnings.filterwarnings("ignore")

#Run kmeans algortihm over 2-10 clusters and store results
inertia = []
silhouette_scores = []
labels_dict = []
for k in range(2, 12):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, init='k-means++', n_init='auto', random_state=42).fit(pca_results)
    inertia.append(kmeans.inertia_)
    labels = kmeans.fit_predict(pca_results)
    labels_dict.append(labels)
    silhouette_avg = silhouette_score(pca_results, labels)
    silhouette_scores.append(silhouette_avg)

#Plot results
metrics = [inertia, silhouette_scores]
y_labels = ['Inertia (Within-cluster Sum of Squares)', 'Silhouette Score']
plot_nums = [1,2]
plt.figure(figsize=(7, 3))
for m, label, n in zip(metrics, y_labels, plot_nums):
    plt.subplot(1, 2, n)
    plt.plot(range(2, 12), m, marker='o')
    plt.xlabel('Number of Clusters')
    plt.ylabel(f'{label}')
    plt.title('')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()


warnings.resetwarnings()
  • The elbow method for inertia shows a clear turn at 3 clusters. However, the silhouette score is highest (after 2) at 6 clusters and the inertia decreases significantly with 6 clusters.
  • Returning to the original aim of the analysis, given that there were 10 original sub-industries, it is reasonable for interpretability for there to be 6 new clusters - where there is low inertia and the highest silhouette score.

3.3 DBSCAN¶

  • Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise (DBSCAN) finds dense clusters, but also allows outliers to remain as noise and unclustered. This can lead to more distinct and compact clusters than other methods, e.g. k-means.
  • DBSCAN requires two parameters to be set: eps and min_samples
    • eps = the max distance between two points to be considered as part of the same cluster
    • min_sample = the minimum number or points required to form a cluster
  • In order to find the optimum parameters for DBSCAN, a range of eps and min_sample parameters are evaluated according to silhouette score. The parameters which result in the best silhouette score are considered optimal.
In [18]:
eps_range = np.linspace(10, 800, 80)
min_samples_range = range(2, 5)

best_eps = None
best_min_samples = None
best_score = -1

for eps in eps_range:
    for min_samples in min_samples_range:
        dbscan = DBSCAN(eps=eps, min_samples=min_samples)
        labels = dbscan.fit_predict(pca_results)
        if sum(np.unique(labels)) > 2:
            silhouette_avg = silhouette_score(pca_results, labels)
            if silhouette_avg > best_score:
                best_score = silhouette_avg
                best_eps = eps
                best_min_samples = min_samples
                best_clusters = len(set(labels)) - (1 if -1 in labels else 0)
                best_noise = list(labels).count(-1)
                best_labels = labels
                
#print results
print(f"Optimum eps: {best_eps}")
print(f"Optimum min_samples: {best_min_samples}")
print(f"Optimum silhouette score: {best_score}")
print(f"(Result) Number of clusters: {best_clusters}")
print(f"(Result) Number of samples in noise: {best_noise}")

#run algorithm with optimum parameters
db = DBSCAN(eps=best_eps, min_samples=best_min_samples).fit(pca_results)
labels_dbscan = db.labels_
sc = db.fit_predict(pca_results)

Define function for calculating inertia

In [20]:
def calculate_inertia(data, cluster_labels):
    num_clusters = np.max(cluster_labels) + 1
    centroids = np.zeros((num_clusters, data.shape[1]))
    inertia = 0

    for cluster_idx in range(num_clusters):
        cluster_points = data[cluster_labels == cluster_idx]
        if len(cluster_points) > 0:
            centroids[cluster_idx] = np.mean(cluster_points, axis=0)

    for i in range(len(data)):
        cluster_idx = cluster_labels[i]
        centroid = centroids[cluster_idx]
        distance = np.sum((data[i] - centroid) ** 2)
        inertia += distance

    return inertia
  • Calculate the inertia and silhouette scores of original sub-industry categories.
  • Calculate inertia and silhouette scores of DBSCAN excluding 'noise' points. Excluding the noise points allows comparison of the silhouette score of clustered points, and can represent a better metric to compare to other clustering methods, whilst also acknoledging in the analysis that some points remain unassigned.
  • Display results in table.

4. Visualise Clustering¶

  • As it is not possible to visualise the clusterings for dimensions 100x100, the plots below use the first two principal components of the PCA results as the x and y axes.
  • This allows a visual representation of the clustering where each point represents a commercial user and the colour represents the cluster membership.
  • It's important to note that colours cannot be compared across graphs e.g. yellow dots on one plot have no relation to yellow dots on another. Rather the key insight is that dots of the same colour on a graph are in the same cluster.

5. Analysis¶

  1. Both K-Means and DBSCAN have formed more appropriate clusterings than the original categories; the inertia and silhouette scores are improved, meaning the clusters are more distinct and better defined in DBSCAN and K-Means. This can be observed from plots above.
  2. The plots highlight the key difference between K-Means and DBSCAN. The DBSCAN is able to exclude 'noisy' points from clusters. As a result the DBSCAN clusters, excluding the noise, are more defined and compact. By contrast, the K-Means algorithm is forced to include all points and therefore the clusters can be less compact, resulting in higher inertia and lower silhouette scores.
  3. The DBSCAN has clustered 76 sites into one group; '0'. Further analysis is required to show the similarity between these sites.
  4. The DBSCAN clustering has shown how sites with different sub-industries have similar profiles e.g. cluster '3' has 1 commerical real estate site, 1 food processing site and 3 shopping centre/mall sites.
  5. There are 9 sites in the 'noise' (-1 above) of the DBSCAN.

6. Conclusion¶

  • Returning to the aim of the study, the DBSCAN results are likely more useful than the K-Means results. As an electricity supplier or operator looking to offer time-of-use tariffs or to introduce DSR to users, the clusters need to prioritise compactness and internal consistency to ensure that product offerings are suitable for that customer segment. Clusters of disimilar customers will be less useful, although the level of disimilarity acceptable would need to be assessed.
  • The DBSCAN results can therefore offer more opportunity because of the compactness of the clusters. The noise points could be treated individually by the electricity provider.
